subSubSection.paragraph:
Description.
Body surface generally smooth and shining, but elytra weakly rough; interspaces between fine punctures distinctly larger than puncture diameter, but larger punctures of anterior edge of pronotum partly overlapping (
Fig. 1A
); large coarse punctures spread all over surface of anterior lobe of prosternum (
Fig. 2F
); punctures of hypomeron near pronotosternal suture large and their interspaces smaller than puncture diameter (
Fig. 2F
). Color. Body generally black, but elytra dark brown, with outer margin paler. (
Fig. 1A, B, C
). Labrum black (
Fig. 2A
). Antennae and mouth parts generally dark brown; mandible black, with apical and internal parts orange (
Fig. 2A
). Legs dark brown, becoming paler apically (
Fig. 1B
). Tergites and sternites VIII‒X yellow brown, but median basal area of tergite VIII and posterior area of sternite VIII translucent (
Fig. 3A, B
). Aedeagus yellow brown (
Fig. 3E, F
). Hairs. Body covered with yellow-white setae (
Fig. 1A, B
). Antennae and mouth parts except for labrum with yellow to brown setae. Setae of legs yellow white becoming yellow apically.

Head. Frons without depression. Supra-antennal carina incomplete medially (
Fig. 2A
); frontclypeal region gradually sloping to base of labrum (
Fig. 2A, B
). Antennomeres I, III, IV and IX–XI longer than wide (
Fig. 2B, C
); II globular, shortest, as long as wide; III obconical, slightly longer than II; IV–X serrate; IV shorter than II–III combined, slightly longer than V. 
Male.
Antennae extending beyond apex of pronotal hind angles by two apical antennomeres (
Fig. 1A
); antennomere IV 1.16–1.35 x as long as wide, 1.74–2.00 x as long as III; V–VIII longer than wide; XI 2.40–2.78 x as long as wide. 
Female.
Antennae not reaching pronotum posterior lateral apices by apical antennomere (
Fig. 1C
); antennomere IV 1.18–1.45 x as long as wide, 1.53–1.68 x as long as III; V–VIII almost as long as wide; XI 1.82–2.14 x as long as wide. Mandible bidentate.

Abdomen. Ventrite V 0.59–0.67 x as long as wide. 
Male.
Tergite VIII (
Fig.3A
) ca. 0.70 x as long as wide; apical margin strongly prominent and broadly rounded. Sternite (
Fig. 3B
) VIII without median notch; posterior angles slightly prominent and rounded. Tergite IX (
Fig.3C
) longer than wide, ca. 1.4 x length of tergite X; median notch rounded. Tergite X (
Fig.3C
) ca. 1.5 x as long as wide; posterior margin rounded. Sternite IX (
Fig.3D
) ca. 2.9 x as long as wide, rounded apically, concave laterally. 
Female.
Tergite VIII ca. 0.95 x as long as wide (
Fig. 4B
). Sternite VIII with side almost parallel on basal half (
Fig. 4C
); spiculum ventrale robust, ca. 2.0 x as long as sternite VIII (
Fig. 4A
).

Genitalia. 
Male
(
Fig. 3E, F
). Basal piece ca. 0.25 x total length of aedeagus. Median lobe exceeding apices of parameres; basal struts ca. 0.20 x total length of median lobe. Parameres separated ventrally, without lateral subapical barb, not expanded apically; apex with several setae dorsally (
Fig. 3G
), with one seta ventrally (
Fig. 3H
), with two setae apically (
Fig. 3G, H
). 
Female.
Baculum robust, ca. 2.4 x as long as coxites (
Fig. 4D
); coxites not segmented (
Fig. 4E, F
), with some setae at each side; stylus with a seta near apex. Vagina with coiled sac extending from ventral side (
Fig. 4D
: arrow); bursa copulatrix globular, without sclerotized structures.
